	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540604_01.jpg"/>
			<p>Dedicated to the fifth anniversary of <date when="1942-02-06">February 6, 1942</date>, the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deportation</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-550" type="subject">aktion</term> to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/456172/riga.html">Riga</placeName>, which we composed in my cafÃ© in the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1032?dlid=eng" type="ghetto">Riga ghetto</placeName>. We composed the
				poem during <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-754" type="subject">Sukkot</term>
				<date when="1942">1942</date>, I, <persName ref="#ehri_et_viner_shane">Shane Viner</persName>, and my friend <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_puchard_volf">Volf Puchard</persName>.</p>
			<p>1.</p>
			<p>I will never forget the violent acts! Going through the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-874?dlid=eng" type="ghetto">Kovno ghetto</placeName> gate they [â¦.]
					us.<note place="bottom">Uncertain. Counted us (if it is ××¢×¦×××)? Colored us? The latter could be a reference to the marking of
					Jews.</note> They arranged us in lines. Commotion, wailing and cries! <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">Children</term>, this reeks of an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-550" type="subject">aktion</term>!</p>
			<p>2. <lb/>They dragged the heretics from the aerodrome to the kloyz! Whoever is one of their own, they take him out. In its predicament,
				the committee already <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selected</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> from the underworld. Small <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term> have no place here!</p>
			<p>3.</p>
			<p>Here the clique revealed its sharp teeth, escorted by rifles, blows, and childish crying! <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">Sorted</term> into groups of twenty and inspected with
				jabs. Oy, to where they are taking us I do not know.</p>
			<p><pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540604_02.jpg"/></p>
			<p>4.</p>
			<p>Here it reeks, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>, of the <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/9610418/ix-kauno-fortas.html">Fort</placeName>,<note place="bottom">Ninth Fort, where most of the
					Jews form the Kovno ghetto were murdered.</note> that was what we thought! We went like sheep, to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> they brought us! They threw into the
				wagons loaves of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> and a purse of
				matches. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">Children</term>, smoke and be quiet!</p>
			<p>5.</p>
			<p>You cannot imagine, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term>, our comfort,
				relieving human needs on the spot! No drop of water in our mouths, sticking your head out is liable to get you a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">bullet</term>! So we travelled for two full days.</p>
			<p>6.</p>
			<p>Arriving in the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2055" type="camp">Riga camp</placeName> imagine my
				luck, the first day I became well acquainted with <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929" type="subject"
					>Provodnik</term>!<note place="bottom">A rubber factory in Riga.</note>
				<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-788" type="camp">Kaiserwald</placeName>, only the [â¦]<note
					place="bottom">Uncertain. </note> Steinbach hits the mark pretty well in the cheek. What does he want, poor thing, from a <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_lithuanians">Lithuanian</term> Jew.</p>
			<p>7.</p>
			<p>Everyone together endured <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">poverty, cold and
					need</term>! Rising very early and returning late at night! We were not lacking any <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-295" type="subject">bedbugs</term> at night, they turned the world over!
				Likewise, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-295" type="subject">bath</term> was not for us.</p>
			<p><pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540604_03.jpg"/></p>
			<p>8.</p>
			<p>Sorrows, just like everything else, nevertheless have a limit! Now they do not herd us to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929" type="subject">Provodnik</term>, the sorrows to an end! No more
				masters, no more <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Poles</term>, to hell with the pick axes and barracks! Many no longer need
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-834" type="subject">ration</term></p>
			<p>9.</p>
			<p>Only in the kingdom of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> does one
				forget the suffering! The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826?dlid=eng" type="subject">men</term> become
					fools<note place="bottom">Or prostitutes, uncertain.</note> when the watch strikes half past eight! <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_margolin">Mrs. Margolin</persName> watches over everything well, she also sings the hit <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject">songs</term>!</p>
			<p>10.</p>
			<p>I have finished the business, set the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> pot
				to cook! Sold shag, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">saccharine</term>, I whistle to
				the world! The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> is not far, I go straight to the other
				side, at least I avoid the evil <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">uncle</term>.</p>
			<p><pb n="4" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540604_04.jpg"/></p>
			<p>11.</p>
			<p>Dry <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">biscuit</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bacon</term>, then farewell! When you still have a
				half a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">flask</term>, youâre set! One <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1053" type="subject">puts aside</term> a packet for the Jewish <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1120" type="subject">policeman</term>! Then your <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1142" type="subject">certificate</term> is valid everywhere! The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-374" type="subject">half-Aryans</term> are my friends.</p>
			<p>12.</p>
			<p>And when I come home completely drunk, I fall straight into bed! Then <persName ref="#ehri_et_jordan">Jordan</persName> and the
				committee come to me in a dream! Elkes, Lurie, and <persName ref="#ehri_et_arenshtam">Arenshtam</persName>, and the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-933" type="subject">trading</term> through the fence! God have mercy on
				them. End</p>
			<p>Mr. Editor, please sent this poem to the Historical Committee in my name to <persName ref="#ehri_et_kaplan_israel">Mr. Israel
					Kaplan</persName>, he is also one of those remaining alive who were on my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term>. I have many more <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-681" type="subject">poems</term> that I composed but I have no paper to
				write, but I will send to you also my experiences which I endured in eleven <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camps</term> and three <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghettos</term>.</p>
			<p><pb n="5" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540604_05.jpg"/></p>
			<p>My memories from <date when="1942-06-02">February 6, 1942</date>, to <date when="1947-02-07">February 7, 1947</date>.</p>
			<p>In the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-874?dlid=eng" type="ghetto">Kovno ghetto</placeName>, only
				a few months after the Great <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-550" type="subject">Aktion</term> in which
				more than ten thousand of our dearest ones were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject"
					>taken away</term>, on <date when="1941-01-25">January 25, 1941</date>, they again began talking about an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-550" type="subject">action</term> to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/456172/riga.html">Riga</placeName>. Later the talk about sending 600 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826?dlid=eng" type="subject">men</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/456172/riga.html">Riga</placeName> intensified. However, we knew what this meant for us and we began
				to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hide</term> ourselves away in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">hiding places</term>. A few days later the atmosphere
				calmed down again, and we gradually came out [of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject"
					>hiding places</term>]. In the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-874?dlid=eng" type="ghetto"
					>Kovno ghetto</placeName> at that time they needed <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1057"
					type="subject">working hands</term> for the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/598316/kaunas.html">Kovno</placeName>
				aerodrome. So as soon as I went out onto the street I was caught and straight away sent to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> at the aerodrome. That day there was a
				burning <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">frost</term> which cut like knives, we all
				went out to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term>. In the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-874?dlid=eng" type="ghetto">ghetto</placeName> there was then a panic.
				They immediately slammed the doors with the bolts, no living soul was to be seen outside, apart from a few <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1120" type="subject">policemen</term>. However, that day we did not <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> in the aerodrome. We just stood and talked
				with one another about the good conduct of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-480" type="subject"
					>guards</term>, how they did not herd us to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject"
					>work</term> as they did on all other occasions. Yet that day also passed slowly and sadly. When 3.30 arrived, they gave us an
				order to lay down the axes and spades and the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject"
					>working</term> day was over. We went straight into the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-874?dlid=eng" type="ghetto">ghetto</placeName>, on the way we directly
				found out that in the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-874?dlid=eng" type="ghetto"
					>ghetto</placeName> something bad had happened, but we did not know what. Close to the door they arranged us in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-550" type="subject">rows</term> of twenty <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>. Opposite the Work Office and in the square
				stood the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-477" type="subject">commandant of the ghetto</term>, <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_jordan">Jordan</persName>, with his retinue and from the Jewish Labor Office Lurie and <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_arenshtam">Arenshtam</persName> and the Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1120"
					type="subject">police</term>,</p>
			<p><pb n="6" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540604_06.jpg"/></p>
			<p>and they herded us straight into through a fenced wire gate, a few <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207"
					type="subject">people</term> straight away tried to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204"
					type="subject">escape</term>. However, immediately a few shots rang out and they took us straight to the kloyz <note
					place="bottom">small synagogue or study house</note>. They beat us with the rifles and they filled the kloyz with <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> so that it was hard to breath; really
				we were suffocating. Immediately, Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1120" type="subject"
					>policemen</term> came and took out their <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject"
					>people</term>. Later, the Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1120" type="subject">police</term>
				came again and it became bitter and dark for us, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1051"
					type="subject">black trade</term> began â how much will you give, you get out straight away, five golden coins and a golden watch
				and the deal is done, hand it over. And now take an armband and a police hat and follow him out. And so it went on, and we still
				remained in the kloyz. A <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll call</term> was
				conducted in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> and they seized more
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> because they had not reached the
				required number due to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1120" type="subject">police</term> letting
				half the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> go <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1053" type="subject">for gold and money</term>, with the agreement of the
				Labor Office, at its head <persName ref="#ehri_et_lurie">Lurie</persName> and <persName ref="#ehri_et_arenshtam">Arenshtam</persName>,
				nicknamed the Hunderter [the hundred] or Mapu. Yet the number had been reached by 7 P.M., and they arranged us again in front of the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-477" type="subject">commandant</term> in rows of twenty <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826?dlid=eng" type="subject">men</term> and march. A few shots, childish
				cries, and the wails of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> were heard. We
				walked and we thought they were taking us to the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/9610418/ix-kauno-fortas.html">Ninth
					Fort</placeName>. However, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-477" type="subject">commandant</term>
				assured us that we should not be afraid: we were going to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943"
					type="subject">work</term> and not to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject"
					>death</term>. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/598316/kaunas.html">Kovno</placeName> would yet be jealous of us. We would forthwith be able to write
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-843" type="subject">letters</term> to our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">families</term>. But promises and love [maybe: being
				nice] do not cost money, especially for the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>.</p>
			<p><pb n="7" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540604_07.jpg"/></p>
			<p>We were well acquainted with <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term> promises but could not help ourselves. So they
				took us in the direction of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/598316/kaunas.html">LaisvÄs AlÄja</placeName>, and we arrived at
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-940" type="subject">train</term> station in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/598316/kaunas.html">Schanz</placeName>, where they loaded us into the wagons, forty <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826?dlid=eng" type="subject">men</term> to a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">wagon</term>. Before they closed the wagons they gave
				us <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> with a purse of matches so that we
				could smoke and be quiet. And when they had loaded us into the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518"
					type="subject">cattle cars</term> there were six hundred of us, including <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">children</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>; there were also a few volunteers like
				the crazy <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> Galu and Mapu. This was
					<date when="1942-02-06">February 6, 1942</date>, and we left at midnight. The wagons were locked from the outside. As soon as the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> started moving away from the
				station, immediately a few lads opened the windows and doors and a series of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> began <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">jumping</term> through the doors and windows. From my
				wagon twelve <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">jumped</term> out straight away; from another wagon
				there <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">jumped</term> out seventeen <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">persons</term> and in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/619711/yanova.html">Jonava</placeName> (<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/619711/yanova.html"
					>Yanov</placeName>) and near <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/594739/siauliai.html">Å iauliai</placeName> (<placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/594739/siauliai.html">Shavel</placeName>) also a few <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">jumped out</term>. I myself also wanted to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">jump out</term>. I was standing ready <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">to jump</term> when all at once I felt that someone
				was holding me by my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">coat</term> and a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">womanâs</term> voice calls out my name, <q><persName
						ref="#ehri_et_viner_shane">Shane</persName>, I wonât let you <term
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">jump</term>, you stay here.</q> I turn around,
				angry. It was a friend of my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">wife</term>, <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_kabinsky_sorel">Sorel Kabinsky</persName>. And later I did not manage to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">jump out</term> and continued on to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/456172/riga.html">Riga</placeName>. It was cold in the wagons and there was no water to drink, only
				dry <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> and it stank in the wagon because
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> had to relieve their needs on the
				spot.</p>
			<p><pb n="8" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540604_08.jpg"/></p>
			<p>We arrived in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/594739/siauliai.html">Å iauliai</placeName> by day and stood for a few hours at
				the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/594739/siauliai.html">Å iauliai</placeName> station. Jewish <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">girls</term> from <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/594739/siauliai.html">Å iauliai</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">worked</term> at the station and they told us about
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-550" type="subject">aktions</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/594739/siauliai.html">Å iauliai</placeName>. Thanks to them we were able to get <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">icicles</term> to drink and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>, and they were herded away from us so
				that we should not be able to talk with them. Later they opened our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522"
					type="subject">wagon</term> and we got some fresh air, relief from the stink, and we received money â 17 marks in our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">wagon</term>. In other <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">wagons</term> they received only 12 marks. This was
				because our wagon had fewer <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> in it
				after a lot had <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">jumped out</term>. And so we
				travelled on further for two days and three nights until we reached <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/456172/riga.html"
					>Riga</placeName>. There began my wandering through eleven <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567"
					type="subject">camps</term> and (3) three <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject"
					>ghettos</term> and my experiences until today I will [not or will later]<note place="bottom">Something seems to be missing here
					so that the sentence will make sense. Perhaps he will write more later.</note> write to you because I do not have paper on which
				to write. And I attach here the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-680" type="subject">poem</term> about
				February 6 which I and another lad form <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/598316/kaunas.html">Kovno</placeName> composed in my
				cafÃ© in the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1032?dlid=eng" type="ghetto">Riga ghetto</placeName>.
				My cafÃ© in the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1032?dlid=eng" type="ghetto">Riga
					ghetto</placeName> was the only one in the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1032?dlid=eng"
					type="ghetto">ghetto</placeName> with <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691" type="subject"
					>music</term> and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-692" type="subject">artists</term> also sang
				there. I ask you, Mr. Editor, that you print it and improve the wording, that means edit it, and please excuse my bad handwriting
				because I am right handed [but] I am sadly an <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-326" type="subject"
					>invalid</term>, I am missing three half fingers from my right hand. In addition to this, I endured things that would fill
				volumes. We were among the first of those sent to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/456172/riga.html">Riga</placeName> and only
				twelve of us <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-904" type="subject">remain alive</term>.</p>
